< Review>
This barbershop has a classic old world feel  with a sports theme that caters to guys. You'll be offerred a water or beer, and there are individual televisions at each station if you want to watch something. No ungodly chemical stink when you walk in thank goodness, one of my pet peeves.

I've had several barbers here, my favorite is Hamid, who always does an excellent job. The real selling point though is that my wife says Hamid cuts my hair better than anyone ever has. That's the best endorsement I can think of. You can expect a bit of pampering here, hot towels, short massage, etc. but this is still a barbershop and not a salon. I like that.

They do offer shaves and such that I haven't taken advantage of yet, maybe I will at some point.

The owner is usually present who mans the front end. He's personable enough and it's nice to see he cares to  keep a watch over his business.

Bottom line: great place for a cut, and try Hamidüòä< /Review>

<name>BrianB64<//name>< review>
WOULD GIVE 6 STARS! Vacationing in Coronado from Arizona.  Took our kids to the beach when it was about 68 degrees outside (which are winter temps to us.)  Wife and I froze but kids had a blast.  Our 5 year old came down with a bad cough.  Drove around for hours the next morning looking for an urgent care that would see him.  NO ONE would.  Our only shot was the ER.  My wife called Sharp and the nurse who answered was extremely helpful, courteous and understanding. Told us to "bring him on in." Landed the suburban out front for the complimentary valet parking and walked into the ER.  Less than an hour later we had chest x-rays to rule our pneumonia,  the doctor (who was a super nice guy) diagnosed mild bronchitis, put prescriptions in our hands and sent us on our way.  I was blown away.  Everyone there was professional and took very good care of our son.  Made him feel comfortable through the whole process. I can't say enough about the staff from the door to the doc.  Thank you for taking care of our little guy.  We'll be hitting the waves again soon.  Only this time we'll wait for some sunshine and temps above 70!<//review>

< text>
In the SGV, Di Pilla's stands out as it's one of the few very good Italian restaurants in an area filled with Asian eateries. A group of us stopped by for a birthday lunch. Their complimentary bread is so good, it's almost addicting. Their pastas are tasty to say the least. I often opt for the half and half which is half spaghetti & half ravioli especially when you can't decide. Today I opted for the beef ravioli with a salad. The pasta is generally al dente which I like.< /text>

<user>115175275508805116327< /user><username>Kimberly</username>< time>
1614530889904<//time>
< rate>
5</rate>
< review>
I don't like antiques myself..I like more modern stuff...however I came with my brother who loves antiques.

This place is huge. It is three levels and has thousands of items here.  It is clean for sure.  Outside is lined with train box cars which was cute.  There are working bathrooms as you walk in.

You can find anything from records to jewelry...dolls...lamps...kitchen items...baseball cards...crib...tabe...chairs...paint...a whole buffet of items....you name it...and it seems like they carry it.

I don't know antique pricing...so I can't really determine if the pricing is good or not.

I did take many photos of what they have in the store just in case you see something you like.

We did not buy anything...but it was super fun looking at all the different items in the store</review>

< text>
I love this place if nothing just to walk through and browse! They have most of their antiques set up in "booths"; a person rents a space and decorates and displays their antiques to sale. There is really cool stuff from all eras, and for all different things. Clothing, dishes, artwork, knickknacks.. You name it. Everytime you think you're done, there still more around the corner. Im not sure if their prices are fair or not because I don't buy antiques. But like i said, it's cool enough just to stop by when you have some time to kill or just want to get out of the house.< /text>

No pizza by 10:30, so I call. David, the owner, tells me he never received the order and blamed me or the 3rd party service he uses to take online orders. I call the 3rd party service, and they say Dave's confirmed the order, but they apologized anyway and gave us a full refund + a 3$ coupon.

<Rating>4< /Rating>< Text>
This store has a large layout. Carrying trendy street gear. Professional sports teams gear. Work gear ( Dickies, medical scrubs). Kids school wear. Along with a large selection of caps. Backpacks and accessories with some fashion jewelry. Van Tennis shoes and purses are just some if the extras they carry. Things are sectioned out for ease of locating. Dressing rooms were closed. Hand sanitizer at door entry. Pricing is reasonable along with some markdowns and sale items. Parking in front of the store is limited.<//Text>

< Text>
I am writing this review before the product is installed and the rating reflects the way the whole process has been managed to date.

I called to get an appointment set up for someone to come out and see what options were available to me and discuss pricing. I was given a time 2 weeks out on a Saturday with a specific time of 12:00 PM; not a window of time but a specific time. On the day of the appointment at 12:58 PM, I called ClearView office and I asked if someone was still coming out and at 1:20 PM I received a call from the tech saying he is running late and will be there in 20 minutes. He showed up just before 2 PM and spent about 15 minutes there discussing the options and collecting the 50% down payment on 2 doors.

On the following Monday, I received a call scheduling the install for a Saturday, 3 weeks out, which is in about 3 days from when I am writing this review for 1:30 PM; again, not a window of time but a specific time. Today, I get a call saying that they need to "pull back" the appointment by a little bit to 3 PM! I think they meant push out to 3 PM, so I called to see what happened and after going through the Abbott & Costello routine with the first person who answered the call getting no logical response for the push out, she had me speak with another person who told me they are very busy this summer and that the same guy that was late the last time will be out between 3 & 5 PM on Saturday! Wait, until now everything has been a specific time, now it is a window of time 3 days before the appointment and I have to change my plans for Saturday to accommodate their poor or inept scheduling management. She said we have too many appointments scheduled for Saturday morning and didn't want to be late so they pushed my appointment out. In other words, they squeezed another 1 or 2 appointments in pushing me out because "we are very busy this summer"!

The experience to date has not been very good and I am hoping the quality of product and installation is not horrible because "it has been a very busy summer" for ClearView. Clearly, customer service is not their concern!<//Text>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
Excellent quick service, I had a reservation but was able to be seated sooner than our appointed time. The food was fresh,not surprised since we are right by the water. Fried calamari had a perfect consistency of batter, texture and flavor. I had to try the crab cake sandwich, I was not disappointed in the moist and crispy cake on a beautiful brioche bun they served me. I had a crack in my glass, I alerted the waiter to prevent any accidents/messes, he replaced the glass and beverage right away. I had to pass on the dessert, I was much too full to proceed. I recommend this place to anyone trying to have a peaceful dinner with terrific service. The price is also great for the quality of food.< /text>

< Text>
Excellent quick service, I had a reservation but was able to be seated sooner than our appointed time. The food was fresh,not surprised since we are right by the water. Fried calamari had a perfect consistency of batter, texture and flavor. I had to try the crab cake sandwich, I was not disappointed in the moist and crispy cake on a beautiful brioche bun they served me. I had a crack in my glass, I alerted the waiter to prevent any accidents/messes, he replaced the glass and beverage right away. I had to pass on the dessert, I was much too full to proceed. I recommend this place to anyone trying to have a peaceful dinner with terrific service. The price is also great for the quality of food.</Text>

<user_name>Christina McGold (Christie)< /user_name><gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /gmap_id><rate>3< /rate>< Review>
Wonderful date place! Weird ally location with a gorgeous marina, overpriced weak ,measured cocktails...only the Manhattan and Martini have ,what I would call, a booze forward sotuation.The menu is ALL seafood. Except for truffle parmesan fries. Very old and famous. And, wow..what a view! If you want a 200 dinner, this is your spot! Dont ask to plug in your cell phone..there is a rule that says No! Hilarious bonus, you can usually park there.....down the Ally, pass the marina..bang a left..and BAM....you get to park. Ay su set there is a fabulous seagull show on the roof as above the trash cans.</Review>

< Text>
Good choice for seafood along the wharf. The classic design and more mature staff lend an air of authenticity beyond some of the other restaurants nearby. I enjoyed the clam chowder, which was rich and full of little morsels of clam. Similarly, the crab thermidor was packed with chunks of crab. [{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNrCMd6uIPmdjFbG-cFlxGrg36-3d7N_FpEieKD=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNnm_NuLnG-wE2FC8ewaCXhz9XDXT90_W1oaFHn=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMfNNOuPYxb569G9442pDaxwQCkI3L8M9KwQp0b=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipML4ZLFYw3MskXyFAwYaGllYztyhuB2josXtM-r=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN1Ilgi6JGYjil2Y8KtP3RdeGwirLw1zsTX4H7T=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMelOGZLA-9UN1Ww_wrfNQ3Latul0b9lfnkmbIY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMW-zbJqbPGzRyywuITIT_sfYAA099OfndWQrPn=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNeRfMCm8LlJmlq3C32KRRdDBGRVIcUWygj5ij2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM4-LjXUa11x8d_rOAcS16LwhFnFeFeccUIVL0g=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOrq2nM65-l3t191jqI9i5SqZbgwOaB79wwpyQi=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics>
<Review>It had been over six months since I had had a meal at a restaurant or made a reservation. With the sun shining, the idea of enjoying a cold crab salad overlooking the water appealed to me. Plus it's a nice image thinking of Al Scoma creating a family business 50+ years ago and having a pier named after him. Could such a story unfold for a scrappy go-getter these days?

We were a few minutes early for our lunch reservation, so we took the time to enjoy the view of the water and the mosaic ode to the city outside. Definitely easy to appreciate on a warm day. A few minutes later, we were seated at a picnic style table and received sourdough bread and whipped butter, and glasses of ice water.

Unfortunately, one of the glasses had remnants of red lipstick on it. We brought it to our server's attention, and later on, he replaced our water. Without a word, he took the glass and walked away. I couldn't help thinking it would have been nice if he had shown some sign of remorse. I understand that dishwashers can leave behind residue, but given these especially germaphobic times, a little sign of concern for the patrons from the staff goes a long way.

$13 Crab Bisque Bowl:
This orange bowl had a creamy tomato flavor with chunks of crab meat, topped with chives and cracked pepper.

$21 Scoma's Dungeness Crab Cake:
A pair of lightly battered and fried crab medallions were served with a small portion of arugula salad on the side and some creamy dipping salad. The crab was still chunky, which was definitely a plus, because that definitely beats crab cakes with pulverized crab mush.

$47 Scoma's Crab Louis Salad "Classic" 1/2 lb:
I knew the Crab Louis was going to be a large portion, even with the smaller "Classic" sized portion, but when I saw the plate set down in front of me, I knew we would have leftovers. The pile of crab meat sat on top of shredded lettuce, decked out with juicy heirloom tomatoes, cucumber slices, a boiled egg, bell peppers, carrots, olives, lemon wedges, and a ramekin overflowing with Louis dressing. It was cool and refreshing, not to mention the crab and the accoutrements were sweet and satisfying. My only complaint was I would have preferred if the carrot were peeled, because the outer layers looked a touch hairy.
I happily packed up the leftovers and looked forward to digging into it for my next meal. Our server joked that we did a good effort, but ate too much of the salad, haha.

I thoroughly enjoyed the food, and I probably would have enjoyed it even more if I had the opportunity to witness seeing the 'Pier to Plate' process unfold. I would rate my experience a 7/10, and would be more of a solid 4/5 had it not been for the dirty glasses. I wish I could say that I will save myself the money and make my own Crab Louis, but I sure do appreciate someone else shelling all that crab.<//Review></record>

<Review>A great restaurant a little off the beaten path on Fisherman's Wharf. That is they own their own boats and seafood processing facility across the street. Excellent seafood prepared extremely well! By the way they also make craft cocktails including a Bloody Mary made with house made gin. There are so many places to choose from but even at lunch hour in the middle of the week, this restaurant is very busy. Scoma's was recommended by our cabbie a lifelong resident of San Francisco. <Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
With so many of the iconic restaurants in the heart of the tourist area closed I was lucky to find Scoma. Sat indoors in the dining room. It was intimate and well appointed. Service!  This was old world service. I can't remember the last time I had service this attentive to detail and my dining experience. The food was excellent. The dining selection is broad and the Chardonnay I selected was perfect. The food was excellent. Scallops were expertly seared, shrimp cocktail was delicious, risotto was just right, dessert snd coffee were an indulgent experience. I loved the entire experience and highly recommend this treasure just steps away from the commercial clatter of the high traffic tourist spots.</Text>

< Text>
A friend suggested this restaurant to me and I'm so glad she did! First of all, the staff was amazing. They were very friendly and, helpful with suggestions.
Had an amazing margarita to start and had the trio for 2 as an appetizer which includes, calamari, crabcakes and bacon wrapped scallops. Now I am usually not a fan of seafood beyond calamari but the crabcakes were amazing and came with a delicious dipping sauce. Also had a delicious caesar salad.

<Text>On a work trip after a full day. We ate dinner here. It was one of the few dining options available to get us out of our hotel room.

They had extra tables setup where parking used to be. So we ate outside. The view was awesome. The service was top notch.

Drinks. Delicious. I had the smoked maple old fashioned. My dining mate (and friend and coworker) had a Southern Comfort and 7up.

Dinner (we couldn't fit dessert) was the grilled king salmon over Scomaronia and the Cioppino.

We ordered a couple apps too. Dungeness crab, oysters and shrimp. All good. All gone.

We so enjoyed our dinner here!

Thank you team Scoma!!

Hopefully you are able to get a new boat soon!!< /Text>< Pics>

<Review>Waiting about an hour on a weekday evening to be seated for dinner. Extremely busy restaurant which impacts the service quality. The service was decent but they could do better.

Food:
Cioppino: generous amounts of fresh dungeness crab, clams, shrimp, scallops, squid, and mussels in a fresh tomato sauce. The thing that suprised me was it was pretty much all seafood and loads of it. The tomato sauce was quite plain though.

Oysters alla Scoma: rockafeller style with cheese. A bit too sour for me but my buddy enjyoed it.

Scoma‚Äôs Famous Clam chowder: solid chowder and nice junks of seafood but I‚Äôve had better in SF

Overall a nice experience and loved the fresh seafood.< /Review>< Gmap_id>

Emanuela Franceschin< /username>
< text>
I have deliberated greatly whether to give it 3 or 4 stars.  The ambience is cozy and location is 5 stars and entering this delightful blue and white cottage you're transported to a time when you would be served something wonderful straight from the trawler at the "old" fisherman's wharf. I ordered the spaghetti marinara, my husband the mixed grill and my kids each ordered the fish and chips. I will declare I am Italian so perhaps I'm being harsh... but i thought my food was so so. The portions were very generous and no one left hungry but the food itself, not spectacular.  The service so so and I'm being generous. Perhaps it's because we brought the kids (not exactly a family restaurant) or maybe because we didn't order alcohol but i just felt we got average, perfunctory service. This is what really let it down for us. We ended up tipping 30% anyway ... but we wont be back. Sorry.<//text>

<rate>5</rate>< Review>
Everything is fantastic at Scoma's. This is a must if you are in San Francisco, excellent Clam chowder, Caesar salad, and freshest sea food you can get. We love it here, family favorite!

Easy to walk to. It's tucked away from the per noise. The atmosphere reminded me of old San Francisco, dark wood, nice comfy bar stools.

The food and service was Great. And they were able to accommodate the large party of diners that were in attendance with us. Definitely recommend reservations. The food was excellent, the wine selection was superb, and the service was efficient and professional. Highly recommend.<//Review>

<userid>104412019682023142160<//userid><user_name>Stefanie Ulrey<//user_name><Time>1592017903277< /Time><Rate>1<//Rate><Review>I would give this place NO STARS if the site would let me!

Up until tonight, I always loved this place. In fact, I had made a commitment to patronize local restaurants that remained open during the Shelter in Place order to help them during this crisis. Scoma's was one of those places. I had ordered "curbside delivery" a couple of times, no problem. Drive up, someone comes out, takes your card, goes inside and runs the check, and then comes right back with your bill to sign and your bag of food. And away you go. I might add that the service was always masked and gloved.

So tonight, I called in an order, arrived in my car at the time I said I would be there. Someone was there to tell me where to park, and there I sat with absolutely no acknowledgement from the staff inside for the next 15 minutes! Meanwhile, there was a birthday party going on right in front of me, and they received two full food deliveries while I was sitting there!

The same parking guy walked by again and I finally got his attention. He went in to check on my order, and a girl came and informed me that I had to COME INSIDE AND PAY to get my order - OH REALLY? SINCE WHEN? What happened to the "curbside delivery" that you have advertised on your website, and that I've patronized at least twice without any problem? She then informed me that it was because I called my order in rather than ordering online - RIGHT! I called my orders before without any problems, so I knew that wasn't it. She finally admitted that they were busy - evidently too busy to handle the transaction as advertised. OK, well then I'm too busy to be your customer! I told her to skip it and drove away without my order.

So this is how you treat your neighborhood patrons who were loyal to you during the SIP? Suddenly the SIP order's relaxed and  you're letting people into your restaurant to order and pay, and people are standing around in the parking lot, less than six feet apart and no masks, partying and getting all your service. I see. And now I hope some of my neighbors will see, too. SHAME ON YOU. If that's how you're going to treat loyal customers, then you will never get my business again. SHAME. ON. YOU!<//Review><pics>None< /pics>< resp>

We looked into what happened there and unfortunately it was a perfect storm of getting slammed and not having the proper training for the staff that was on hand at the time. We do happily offer curbside service and do handle the transactions as advertised. It will not happen again. Next time you order or come by, please introduce yourself so we can apologize in person and make sure you have a 100% perfect experience. Thank you and we look forward to serving you again."}<//resp>

<Time>1592067396032</Time><Rating>1< /Rating><text>This restaurant shares the pier with fishing boats (that also pay rent) and park here so that we can all get fresh fish. It's a pier after all. Now they want to stop the boats from being there and that's very unfair. These are hard times for everyone we all need to innovate and yes they might need some more outdoor space but also be reasonable and share. None</Pictures>
<Response>{'time': 1592089091527, 'text': 'Catherine, please know Scoma\'s is perhaps the biggest supporter of the local fishing fleet in the entire city. We are more than happy to have any fishing boat being on the pier and several do. We have been letting FV Pioneer sell seafood in our parking lot, which we pay for, at no cost to them. We have no ability, desire or authority to put anyone out of business, and the Pioneer could easily move to a different slip if it wanted to.\n\nIt is an unfortunate situation but we have well over 100 employees, many local fishing crews and countless farmers whose livelihoods depend on our being able to conduct business. After offering several solutions to the FV Pioneer no agreement could be reached.\n\nPlease read this unbiased statement from the Port of San Francisco if you are interested in knowing the facts of the situation.\n\nThank you for your feedback we we hope this response and the Port\'s statement below gives you clarity on the situation.\n\nStatement issued by the Port of San Francisco yesterday:\n\n"This is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\n\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\n\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\n\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales."\n\nFor additional information please contact the Port of San Francisco Public Affairs Office.'}</Response><gmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<userid>110661951617374454080</userid>< Name>
Scott</Name>
<date>1582507558976<//date><Rating>4< /Rating>< text>
I'm a local, and I eat on the San Francisco waterfront often. This is definitely one of the best meals I've had near the Pier 39 / fisherman's wharf area.

Fried calamari was very good, although it could have been just a touch more crispy.

Crispy fries with truffle oil and parmesan cheese were out of this world.

The beet salad was small for the price, but tasted amazing.

The bread roll tasted fresh, but it was not warm.

Service was fast and friendly. I was dining alone and I got one of the tables facing out toward the fishing boats.

The location makes this one of those places that you will not stumble onto. You must see the sign and walk toward the Bay down the pier.

The restaurant is like time stopped in 1965, but it's clean and well-maintained inside.

food is expensive, but not over-the-top expensive. I ordered three appetizers, calamari, crispy fries, and the beet salad. And with two diet Pepsi's it came to $51, before tip.

I will definitely be back here.< /text>

<user>112023208427816013702< /user><user_name>Donna Baldwin< /user_name>< date>
1566087965773<//date>
< rate>
4<//rate>
< review>
I had a quick pre Birthday bite.  We just shared a salad and appetizers.  The crab cakes were delicious.  The calamari's corn meal breading was odd to me.  Not fine milled and I wasn't expecting the texture.  The bacon wrapped scallops were tasty but seemed warm. They would've been better with a little more heat...like a little sizzle or something.  The one thing I did enjoy but did not photograph was the Casa Margarita.  It would be one of the reasons I'd go back.  The atmosphere was nice and very old San Fran.  Although it is in the Wharf, it is a bit off the beaten track so you don't feel like you are hanging out with a bunch of tourists.  Many apologies if that offends, I just hate being with the masses.  I know...I should share such a wonderful city, but I'm selfish that way üòá.<//review>

<Text>In my opinion this has to be one of the best restaurants in the US. Tucked away down a small street at Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco, Scoma's is like finding buried treasure. The restaurant itself is not overly ostentatious but the warm friendly staff make you feel imediately welcome.

<UserId.>115841246477616920126<//UserId.><name>Kevin Grim<//name><Time>1505453547124< /Time><rate>5<//rate><Review>Before going on our honeymoon, we were told by several people that all the places to eat at or around fisherman's wharf are essentially the same...while that isn't a bad thing, the sole exception is Scoma's. While all the seafood around the wharf is likely fresh, at Scoma's not only do you know it is but the service and preparation they put into each meal is unmatched. Our server dutifully told us exactly which dishes were locally caught and prepared fresh vs frozen. I started with the clam chowder and can honestly say it was one of the best I ever had. For entrees, my wife and I had the locally caught, fresh blackened cod.  Perfectly cooked and spiced, it was so good, I had to slow myself down to enjoy it more...as well as stop myself from just going caveman on it and eating it with my bare hands. Also, as a bonus, our awesome waiter (who had previously asked what brought us to San Fran after learning that we lived in NJ) brought us some incredible sorbet and ice cream to congratulate us on our marriage/honeymoon. This added an entire new level to our experience. When we are in San Fran again, we will definitely be returning!< /Review>< pics>

<review>Three is being generous. Traveling in San Francisco and Scoma's was highly recommended by our hotel staff and the glowing Google reviews. Our waiter, Timothy was less than interested in us as customers, not helpful in advising us on menu selections and overall, just a dud.  We should have asked to change to the waiter people nearby had- he was outgoing, knowledgeable and sold the menu items with skill and was not pushy. As for our entrees, my shrimp and scallops were OK, my client got the mixed grill which was over cooked and on a par with hotel banquet fare. Dessert was limited, and the tiramisu was suspiciously like what Olive Garden served. For nearly $200, this was disappointing. The salmon mac and cheese was actually great, so possibly I should have settled for this and a salad. <userid>105928218245157209851< /userid>< user_name>
Jason Deonarain< /user_name>
<time>1556431014458<//time><rating>3<//rating>< review>
Let me start by saying coming from NY especially near many Italian and seafood inspired places I came in with very high expectations.  Although the food was good by many standards, it was not WOW.  Typical seafood fare, and flare.  Service was fast, courteous, and prices were what one would expect for the area and for seafood.  I had a plate of pasta and assorted seafood.  Seafood was fresh tasting and the pasta was good.  I also has a cup of the crab bisque which was very rich and filling- the highlight of the night.  My fiance had a grilled platter of assorted fish- which was light, flaky but nothing to rave about.  All in all, if you're in the mood for seafood I would recommend Scoma.  However, if you're in the mood for dishes incorporating seafood to set a new bar- I'd say try somewhere else.< /review>

Below is a statement from the Port of San Francisco outlining the facts of the situation:\n\n"This is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales."\n\nThank you for your interest and please contact the Port of San Francisco if you have any questions regarding this situation.'}</Response><UserId.>116893164318683976555</UserId.>< Name>

<text>Discovered this place while visiting San Francisco. It is just off the main drag, so it is easy to miss, if you aren't looking for it, specifically. That is a good thing. The restaurant is quieter and much higher quality food than the places among the main road. The history behind this place is fascinating.

The seafood is fresh caught and delicious.

The staff was very friendly.

I did not have a reservation, but I arrived early enough that I only had about a 20 minute wait. Call ahead if you want to guarantee a timely seat.

I will definitely go back next time im in the city.< /text>< Pics>

< text>
Probably the finest restaurant  in San Francisco.  The staff is very polite  and make you glad you came. The food is to die  for. The best seafood in the Bay Area. The chef's  do a great  job of preparing the food as you ordered lt. No ready made  meals here. Everything is cooked to order.  The restaurant  is very clean and neat. Top it all off they park your car for free. It's not cheap but we'll worth the price. I've been coming to Scoma's for over 50 years never been disappointed.< /text>

<userid>102796908560252567596</userid><user_name>Elle G</user_name><time>1566235292888<//time><rating>4</rating>< Review>
I was conducting my San Francisco Photo Tours for my Florida clients and a Lyft Driver recommended Scoma's for the best clam chowder in San Francisco. The restaurant was hard to find but we finally found it. Service was real slow when we arrive like 9 pm. It was busy and we finally got our clam chowder. Lots of black/white celebrity photos on the wall. And also the Bar area was really nice and quiet and luxurious.  This place has history and prices are $$$ so be sure to have at least $ 100 in your wallet. It's worth a visit on your next trip to San Francisco</Review>

< Review>
I was conducting my San Francisco Photo Tours for my Florida clients and a Lyft Driver recommended Scoma's for the best clam chowder in San Francisco. The restaurant was hard to find but we finally found it. Service was real slow when we arrive like 9 pm. It was busy and we finally got our clam chowder. Lots of black/white celebrity photos on the wall. And also the Bar area was really nice and quiet and luxurious.  This place has history and prices are $$$ so be sure to have at least $ 100 in your wallet. It's worth a visit on your next trip to San Francisco<//Review>

< review>
I'm an SF local, so this isn't a place I would normally visit. However, after visiting with my family, I can say that this place is worth a trip. The location out on the pier gives it a truly classic SF feel. Looking back at the city and out toward the Bay is spectacular. The decor is dated, but charming. The food is very good (but not great). Come to this place for the classic experience and you won't be disappointed.</review>

<name>Kaity Forde</name><Date>1581804607741</Date><Rate>1<//Rate>< Review>
I'm genuinely confused by how highly rated this is. Even for the fisherman's wharf or Pier 39, the food was pretty terrible. The clam chowder was alright if you could overcome the grittiness of what I assumed was poorly cleaned clams. I will say that the truffle fries were good, but slightly oily. I got the petrale dore, which was recommended by our waiter, and it was absolutely horrible. I would not recommend this dish unless you like to pay $35 for oily, deep fried cardboard. The only redeeming thing on the plate was the tartar sauce, but that wasn't enough to cover the horrendous taste of the petrale. When I told the staff who took my staff that I didn't want leftovers a sit was just not good, nothing was done about it. Seriously, make the trek to Woodhouse, Waterbar, or anywhere on the grotto if you want good seafood.<//Review>

<rate>5<//rate><text>I visited in June of 2014. It took me a bit to get past the dated decor...

It was a little hard for a first timer to San Francisco to find, but turned out to be a hidden gem.

The food was absolutely out of this world. Dishes were spot on. Some of the best and freshest seafood I have tasted anywhere. Pasta was cooked perfectly (not over done like most places will serve).  Sauces tasted fresh.

This was the first restaurant I visited on my first visit to San Francisco, and it set the bar high for my expectations of the quality of seafood for the area. Some restaurants came close but none matched.

I would highly recommend this restaurant!< /text>< Pictures>

<user>113276752975672209787<//user></record></dataset><record>
<time>1520787517942<//time>< text>
I was taken to this restaurant for my anniversary.  Believe me when I say I tried to get out of it.  I didn't want to sit in a restaurant that smelled of fish or had creatures swimming awaiting their doom.  So I balked all the way to San Francisco.  When we arrived I thought it's a "Hole in the Wall" from the area we had driven into.  Then a valet came to park the car which I found odd because the restaurant appeared very small from the outside.
Boy, was I fooled.

Inside, you have a reservation counter and a cozy waiting place upstairs with vintage pictures on the wall.  There may be a 30 - 45 minute wait but you are not uncomfortable.  Drinks may be ordered from the waiting area and it's not drafty.  Upon going to the dining room, the doors were slid back and what a view!  Elegant dining room with a back wall view of the bay.  Service was on point and at the time Walter was my server.  He was the most charming man ever.  I had the Lobster Provolone Dinner and it was hands-down 5 star!  We had a Lovely evening.

Two weeks later in-laws from Germany arrived and after hearing about Scoma's took us out to this restaurant.  We all had a delightful time and this is now my favorite restaurant.  The crab salad is a must!  One salad fed 4 adults and we were almost too full for the meal.  Excellent!  10 Star!!< /text>

Scoma‚Äôs restaurant is a must do for any foodie traveling through San Fransisco. Located in Fisherman‚Äôs Wharf this homy restaurant is within a hub of sight seeing to do‚Äôs. <rate>5< /rate>< review>
Top notch!  We make plans to dine at Scomas every time we are in San Francisco. We are never disappointed in the meals and service. This time around my husband had the Chopino and he loved it. I had the Fish & Chips lunch special which was great portions of tender fish in crispy beer batter. Soo Good! Their clam chowder is very delicious also, we shared a cup just because we have to have chowder with sour dough when we come to the wharf & this one hits the mark. I suggest you walk past all those noisy eateries along the main street to this legendary restaurant, follow the signs to Scomas.< /review>

The plancha seared calamari were really good and I also had the crab Thermidor and shared crab plate and both were fine. People here are a mixture of tourists and adult old time Californians and the menu is the traditional old time french inspired seafood cuisine. <username>Julia Lloyd-Cowden</username><user>110444854147788105330<//user><gmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34</gmapID><Resp>None< /Resp>< rating>

< Review>
Nothing was particularly wrong, but nothing was spectacular either. We tried Scoma's based on several recommendations by friends. Our waitress was great, very attentive and knowledgeable about the menu. We order drinks to start while deciding what to eat, the drinks were delivered quickly, they're fine...a little light on the alcohol based on how much they're charging and not made as well as other places. We order an appetizer to split and order our entrees at the same time. Our appetizer never comes... It ends up being delivered with our entrees. Not what we wanted with an appetizer but ok. I order the cioppino, and it was tasty. He orders the steak (doesn't like seafood), and it's just ok... The steak was cooked well enough but not great, the parmesan polenta was not very good (I've made better at home) and the mushrooms were just ok (he didn't like the texture of how they were cooked). We decide on dessert, our waitress expounds on how great their pastry chef is.... It's a lie, the desserts were no better than grocery store bought desserts. Overall a disappointment based on recommendations and reviews, and their own reporting.<//Review>

<review>I've been going to Scomas since I was 6 years old. Now I'm 58 years old.  I always have had a great time and great food.  Not this day last Saturday.  We were seated in lousy seats, we wanted hot coffee and got warm coffee we asked for it to be microwaved and the waiter said no we then asked him to take the coffee away then he came back with hot coffee.  Our order was taken very poorly attitude waiter, we ordered ciopino and we had this dish over the past 20 years and it tasted like tomatoe soup. The waiter asked how the meal was and we asked if the cook was new and we were told he'd been there a couple years. The waiter asked why are we asking and we explained the ciopino was just tomato soup with sea food.  Waiter said he would let the chef know. We are ok with that. Our meal was 160.00 we left a 40.00 tip. The waiter came outside and siad  thank you and we were happy about that. During our meal we heard a loud french accent waiter yelling at a dark beared waiter making comments to him that he would kill him, and tear him apart basic threats and that was disappointing.  So i am sad to say Scomas has lost its pasaz and quality and ambiance after my 50 years of going there. I felt i was treated lack luster because of my attire but rest assured we are well off. <user_id>107047962797105177387<//user_id>< Review>
We have a tradition of eating lunch at Scoma's when we fly in to San Fran from the east coast.  It's our first stop.  It's always been great but this past Friday night (dinner for the first time), it was a major disappointment.  Not one of the five of us enjoyed our meal.  Dry, tasteless fish and blah-broth, lazy man's cioppino. Small portions of bland, dry fish for $40.00!  I don't think so.

The staff is great and the atmosphere is cozy and fun.  Major help needed in the kitchen.  There are too many places to eat in San Fran that are excellent and unfortunately, there is little excitement or interest in eating at Scoma's again.< /Review>

<name>Kirsty Jack</name><time>1508816806849<//time><rating>5<//rating>< Review>
This place is incredible .
I don't really like seafood but I loved every single thing I ate (& I even ate a tentacle!). My other half loved seafood and loved it too.The food is fantastic and there is a lovely atmosphere.
There's a classy 60s feel inside (the waiters are in white jackets and  and just so lovely and knowledgeable). Scoma have their own boat and you can literally watch the fish come off the boat, into their processing plant and into the restaurant. You can't get fresher.
Don't let the lack of outdoor seating put you off. We arrived at sunset on a lovely night & wanted to sit outside ...... But actually a seat in the lounge by the window was incredible. We watched a lovely sunset and kept warm.< /Review>

<date>1566401834990</date><Rating>4</Rating><text>My sister and I has a late dinner here tonight. We added ourselves to the handy yelp waitlist at 8:00pm and were 17th in line.  We were instructed to be at the restaurant at 8:30pm.

We arrived late because or lyft driver was very slow but they still honored our waitlist spot.  We had a very professional and attentive waiter but not extremely personable.  I ordered the 3 fish grill (cod, salmon and halibut) and a cup of clam chowder. I loved the halibut and the salmon was above average the cold tasted a teeny bit underdone but that may have been the texture since it is a flaky fish.  She ordered calamari app, ceasar salad and a cup of clam chowder. She enjoyed everything as well but we both agreed the clam chowder was the belle of the ball.

<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
Hidden behind Fisherman's Wharf with a view of the water this place is worth the few extra steps and sometimes short wait.  Once you are seated you are greeted by the most friendly staff and walked through the delicious daily specials(many of them right off the boat).  They have a nice wine menu and you are given a nice basket of bread to munch on while your food is being prepared.

A little bit pricey, but well worth it compared to the other tourists traps around the Wharf this place is worth the money.  The Cioppino is to die for and comes in a huge portion, The fresh swordfish is also a favorite menu item.< /Text>

The best possible seafood in San Francisco. Scomas is a landmark in Fisherman's wharf. They have the freshest seafood, right off the boat. Beautiful views day or night. The bay is lapping right up to the parking lot - and yes, they have free parking, just remember to tip the hard working valets. They can have long waits to be seated, you're welcome to call ahead and ask what the wait time is. The long waits to be seated are because they are the best seafood restaurant ever. People come from all over the world to eat at Scoma's.
Try it.  You won't be disappointed.<//review>

<Date>1554346266510</Date><rate>5</rate>< Review>
Oh my! What a find!   We were near Fisherman's Warf looking for a good bite to eat and Yelp suggested this place.   When we walked in I was a little worried that we were underdressed because the wait staff was bow ties and sharp as could be.  But I figured, "meh, my money's green."
Our waiter was very kind and kept our kids supplied with a delicious crusty bread. We barely scratched the menu but the fish and chips and clam chowder were absolutely excellent.  I for one am pretty hard to please with those two items and Scoma's nailed them.
Overall our lunch in SanFran was one of the best experiences of the trip.<//Review>

<Rating>5</Rating><Name>Katie Mitchell</Name>< Time>
1459979712823<//Time>
< text>
From first glance of the neighborhood, I wasn't sure about this place. My gut said this is going to be cheesy, but I had seen really good reviews online.

It blew me away. Really good classic dishes, with authentic flavor. The crab cakes had just enough crab and the sauce was not tooo rich. Get the fried artichoke hearts, they were light but still crispy!

This is great for a date, anyone who wants to get a waterfront view, and a cozy place.< /text>

<Name>Paul Johnson</Name>< time>
1484867308477< /time>
<Rating>1< /Rating>< Text>
Service was fine, but not equipped to solve the food questions.

I had the Classic Crab Louie Salad (~$40). The crab was tasteless. I ate about 1/3 and gave up. Server assured me it was not frozen, but the lack of taste suggested to me it probably canned. Server suggested they may have 'washed' the crab reducing the flavor?

My friend had the Poor Man's Cioppino (~$40), which was an apt description. Lots of seafood in a thick sauce that could have been V8 juice. The brussel sprouts($9) were very good, you can't really go wrong when you add bacon to anything. Tasty bread and butter. Definitely a tourist trap, would not recommend.

Total bill a bottle of sparkling water ~$107, no alcohol. Yes, we could have sent it all back and walked out, some days you just don't have the energy for that.

Tonight we have reservations at 'Dirty Habit' and much higher expectations.< /Text>

< user>
103054852780999656447< /user>
<name>Nichoulas Musselman< /name><date>1551692702119<//date>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< text>
Love this place! Very fresh seafood, very tasty. Love the mafioso appeal. The walls filled with countless autographed celebrity photos offer amusing eye appetizers while awaiting our entrees. Best clam chowder I've ever had in The City. It's a little hidden but in a good way, likely keeping out wandering tourists or weekend hippies from chancing upon it, making it next to impossible to get a window table on a walk-in. Of all of the many eateries around San Francisco's great Wharf, Scoma's is the the only one I personally consider worthy of historical significance. Yes, Boudins began here and may still be the more popular restaurant even today, however in my opinion Boudins has grown into the Budweiser of bread. Scoma's has something no other Embarcadero restaurant has, a pulse, an identity, character, and bay city charm.  Stepping into Scoma's feels like stepping out of the city. A peaceful, quiet, sense will greet you as you enter as if time itself slows. Forwarding through time, neighboring eateries will likely fade away while Scoma's remains, gaining fame, iconic status, and historical importance. What Randy's Donuts is to LA, or what Katz Delicatessen is to Manhattan, so should Scoma's be to SF. From the cresting waves of the mighty Pacific Ocean, along California's golden coastline, a small port town filling with migrant ruffians and Forty-Niners quickly grew outward and upward. It grew across steep terrain, eventually gaining root spanning the entire Southern Peninsula. Where Giant Pacific Redwood forests once grew, now grows a mighty metropolis. A civilization so grand that Westerners know simply as, "The City," and it was here, hidden down a narrow alleyway, treaded upon by those who've come to know of it. There, built directly onto the wooden planks of a dock, nearest the point where city becomes sea, that is where you'll find it...  Scoma's. To all you soon to be first timers, you're welcome.<//text>

<user_id>104607424381319946855</user_id>< username>
Frank Eargle<//username>
<Date>1550341564761<//Date><Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
Started with a perfect Bloody Mary while waiting 45 minutes for a table.  Never has a wait been so worth it!

We had a bowl of clam chowder.  Fresh clams and organic ingredients. It was far and away the best I have had!

The entre was Pasta Diplomatica which is sort of an Alfredo white sauce.  Fresh ground pepper and fresh grated cheese added to the mix. It was a huge portion of one of the best entre's I have ever had!  Simply delicious!

The wait staff, of which there are plenty, are always there before you need them.  Always filling glasses or taking care of things, but never intruding into the meal.

It was the best meal I have had in a very long time!  Only shame was we had no room for desert.  And the desert menu was sooo tempting.

I will never come to San Francisco and miss Scoma's restaurant!</review>

< userid>
106081215285708585971</userid>
<rating>2<//rating>< Review>
If you think Olive Garden is fancy, then you're in for a treat.
Every thing about Scoma's is dated and out of style but screams a desperate attempt at the appearance of class. Wood paneling, conference room seating and walls of photographs of celebrities no one under 40 can name.
The food was fresh and edible, but the dishes are the very definition of boring and poorly executed by what I assume are novice chefs.
The waitstaff are, from my experience, old, slow, dressed in the typical steak house white jacket/black pants and walk with a sad, hunched, shuffling gait.
Scoma's antiquity would be endearing, if the food were not so painfully boring.< /Review>

< review>
My husband & I just by chance found out about this "fabulous" place to eat. O'my is it ever wonderful, the food is spot on and the service is great. <Text>Great place to eat! Chef's recommendation is a must, we had great time here as per friend's suggestion to come. :)< /Text><response>None</response><name>Maja Bejatovic</name><rate>5</rate><Gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34</Gmap_id><user>103514848511104144731< /user>< Pics>

<Time>1534177577474<//Time><UserId.>111898597580333312700< /UserId.>< gmap_id>
0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34<//gmap_id>
<Text>Popped in right before they were closing to grab a couple glasses of wine and some calamari. Best part of the evening is the fact we were driven here in a brand new Bentley flying spur, which was awesome, so it began with us leaving AT&T park after watching USC crush CAL (Fight On), so we proceeded to try and catch a cab, but with no luck we walked down to the  St. Regis to catch a drink and instead were greeted by the doormen offering the house car for a tour of San Francisco. We accepted.
The driver opened the doors to the beautiful car, we got in, and drove us all over the city showing us different sites and telling us a little history about each location, while my fiance and I sat in back worried that we smelled funny after our rooftop tailgate before the game with friends, but he didn't seem to notice, and we certainly weren't going to bring it up.
After he took us to a few wine bars he inquired about our lust for seafood and asked if he could suggest a spot, so we obliged and he took us to Scoma, but not before making sure a table was ready for us. We arrived and were greeted by an amazing staff and enjoyed some great bites to eat while sipping a fantastic Malbec.
The long and short of it is this, we had a great evening with great food and wine, which cannot be beat by much.</Text><pics>None< /pics><Rate>4</Rate><user_name>John R. Scott</user_name>< Resp>

<Name>Steve Pendleton< /Name><Date>1294347651536</Date><Rate>3</Rate><Text>This is an old restaurant that is trying to be old-style elegant. It isn't anything but old style anymore. Yes, the waiters wear white jackets, but the paneling in the dining room just looks...old. The prices are high, even for Fisherman's Wharf. Typical entree is $30+. The service is not excellent. When we arrived it was a very light Monday night crowd, but the hostess would not seat us until our friend who was parking the car arrived five minutes later. {'time': 1570284410664, 'text': "Hi Elda. Thank you for your visit. Please accept our apologies if you felt our hostess wasn't as polite as she could have been. Hopefully it was just a misunderstanding. Our policy, that most top restaurants in town share, is to only seat a party when it is complete. Otherwise, our servers have to come by extra times as the other people arrive, throwing off the entire flow of the restaurant. We hope you understand. However, we offer complimentary valet parking right at our front door so there should never be any wait at all. Hopefully your meal went well when your party arrived and we hope to see you back soon!"}</resp>

<Pics>None</Pics><user_id>105085349535444602120< /user_id>< Gmap_id>
0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /Gmap_id>
<Date>1517080810202</Date>< Text>
Scoma's is a legacy, but they are just fundamentally being outgrown. Wish they would pare down the menu, update the decor a little bit, and put a little more attention on the waitstaff's skills.

Service was good, appropriately polite and attentive, but kind of clumsy in execution for the intended ambience. E.g. reaching over other guests to serve plates and grate cheese, or forgetting which plate goes where, or just generally awkward interruptions in table conversation and rushed ordering. To be fair, we sat at the bar tables instead of waiting for our reservation.

Food was good but not great. My Bolognese was obviously fresh but the papardelle was sticking and the sauce wasn't much to write home about. Table bread was cold.

I recognize that I'm likely being picky on the details, but based upon the price of the meal, my expectations were higher.

Not 5 stars, but otherwise a good meal and quality service.<//Text>

< Review>
Zagat must be slipping... apparently a 25 means: salads made from brown, wilted, store-bought pre-prepared mixes that sat in the back of the fridge too long, mediocre wine selections and crab so overcooked you have to chew on it like a strap of leather.  If you want better seafood, go to a Red Lobster.  Scoma's was singularly terrible in that regard.  No complaints about the atmosphere or the waitstaff though, they did a great job.  It was too bad that when they asked me how everything was, the only nice thing I could say was that the bread was great (and it was).<//Review>

<Time>1517080810202< /Time><review>Scoma's is a legacy, but they are just fundamentally being outgrown. Wish they would pare down the menu, update the decor a little bit, and put a little more attention on the waitstaff's skills.

Service was good, appropriately polite and attentive, but kind of clumsy in execution for the intended ambience. E.g. reaching over other guests to serve plates and grate cheese, or forgetting which plate goes where, or just generally awkward interruptions in table conversation and rushed ordering. To be fair, we sat at the bar tables instead of waiting for our reservation.

Food was good but not great. My Bolognese was obviously fresh but the papardelle was sticking and the sauce wasn't much to write home about. Table bread was cold.

I recognize that I'm likely being picky on the details, but based upon the price of the meal, my expectations were higher.

Not 5 stars, but otherwise a good meal and quality service.</review>< gmap_id>

<text>Walked in off the street and had about a 15 minute wait to be seated. It was a fairly busy day so there was no place to sit while we waited. They use a texting service to let you know your table is ready, so we just walked around outside.

We started with the fried calamari and it was very good - they cooked it differently then we've ever had it before - big pieces (great dipping sauce too).

After the calamari, we were all actually pretty full so we weren't as hungry for dinner as we would have liked. We had swordfish, shrimp in egg batter and ahi. All were cooked well and tasted good, but not amazing.

Skip this place. It was recommended to us and we went to this classic and long-established restaurant. A short wait at the bar and we were eating. The service from Jose was friendly, but the food was at best average, and the prices are high ($110 (incl tip) for dinner for 2, no apps or dessert and 2 beer/wine each). The fresh wild salmon was utterly unremarkable, slightly overcooked and with little flavor (I could have easily done better at home any number of ways), and the pasta with sausage was OK but overwhelmed by black olives. Perhaps other things on the menu are better, but at these prices I can't see coming back to eat my way through the menu to find something better than average. Spend your money elsewhere.
Service: A
Quality of Food: C-
Value for Money; F<//text>

<Name>Vicki Bissett< /Name>< gmap_id>
0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34</gmap_id>
<Date>1497497828641</Date>< Review>
I had black cod with lemon aoli over smashed potatoes. Van, our waiter (maybe Dan - older gentleman from Chicago) told me it was good, gave me a description, and I, a lady who doesn't like strong tasting fish, LOVED IT!!!!  We started with soup, my husband had clam chowder, I had the lobster bisque. Excellent start to a wonderful meal. We finished with the 7 layer cake; chocolatey, hazelnutty, creamy, crunchy, but not over sweet. The perfect end to a perfect meal! The only part of the meal not extraordinary was the bread - just ordinary bread that was cold in the center. Thank you Scomas for an absolutely delicious meal. Parking is valet - when you start down Al Scomas Way, go over the bridge, make the turn and the valets take it from there. No charge (we tipped).</Review>

< UserId.>
115685129152446132340</UserId.>
<user_name>Diana Duebelbeis</user_name><date>1492801649537</date><Rating>2< /Rating>< text>
This is an "Old School" Italian Seafood Restaurant.....perfect.....our two most favorite foods (Italian and Seafood) and we LOVE anything "Old School."
Upon entering.....you immediately get the 60's vibe.  We went for My 50th Birthday lunch....so had every intention of hanging for a bit with a bottle of wine and of course some Birthday dessert.....all those things that really help to run up the bill....and we didn't care one bit. We were seated in the back upper level. The dining room was not very big and they made sure to seat everyone in one section so it was hard to have any real conversation. We ordered a cocktail while looking over the menu. We both decided on Seafood. My husband ordered the Salmon and I ordered the Dungeness Crab Salad, with a bottle of wine to come w/the meal. Our lunches were brought to the table and as soon as the server walked away, my husband looked at his fish and said "this doesn't look good"  I looked at the fish and could see what he was talking about.....it looked so dried out. He took a few bites and it was awful. My salad was ok....it was supposed to be shelled crab. Of course every bite I took, I had to pull shell out of my mouth. Shelled=Means no shell or cartilage. I can understand a bite or two w/shell but this was ridiculous. The server forgot the wine and we were so glad.....because we were so unhappy that we just wanted to get out of there.  We couldn't believe this is what was served for the price. Our bill was was $125......before tip.  We didn't bother to send the food back because we figured everything was going to come out just as bad.  So totally disappointed! I think the chef needs more training or they need to have better quality control. Would NEVER recommend this establishment.< /text>

< Review>
I have been to Scoma's now four times over the course of nine years. I have had wonderful experiences every time. The views are beautiful and the seafood is GREAT! I have never had such good seafood. I have had the  Dungeness crab cocktail, Gulf shrimp pastina, and the whole dungeness crab. Each of which were AMAZING! I would recommend this restaurant to anyone in the area. I think it goes unrecognized because it is down an alley toward the warf. I will be back sometime again in the future.</Review>

Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. (Translated by Google) A classic Italian seafood restaurant on the water in San Francisco. They have a great selection of fish, seafood, crab and a single steak.
The dishes are on the expensive end - $ 35-40 for a main course, but the portions are large so you can plentifully settle for a lunch. We got Linguine alla Vongole and Pasta Putanesca. The wine is pricey and OK. The beers are cheaper. Their double IPA is fantastic. Try a cocktail while you wait. The lemon kiss (Bacio al Limone) is excellent.
The service is classic, good and attentive.
Can be recommended if you can afford it.

<response>{'time': 1592014209971, 'text': 'Kristina, it seems like you are referring to the issue FV Pioneer has brought up. Please know Scoma\'s has long been one of, if not the biggest supporters of the local fishing fleet, including FV Pioneer. Below is a statement from the Port of San Francisco outlining the facts of the situation:\n\n"This is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales."\n\nThank you for your interest and please contact the Port of San Francisco if you have any questions regarding this situation.'}< /response><userid>116735751752445026374<//userid><username>Kristina Feller</username><pics>None< /pics><Time>1591986500602<//Time></record>
